![The scalloped hammerhead is Critically Endangered. (© Thomac Kotuc)](./imgs/sp_marine_img_2.png){fig-align="center"}

</center>

## Trends – the Red List Index

The Red List Index (RLI) [@butchart2004a] for top predators such as sharks, shows deteriorating threat status over time (@fig-2). As apex and meso-predators, sharks perform a range of essential ecological functions in marine food webs, including controlling the populations of their prey, maintaining diversity at lower trophic levels (including commercially fished species), and maintaining functional coastal and marine ecosystems [@forestry2022a]. Loss of top predators therefore has potential knock-on effects on the livelihoods of fisheries-dependent communities and food security.

The decline in shark populations is a global trend [@dulvy2024a]. Globally, the main threats to sharks are fisheries (as both target catch and bycatch), habitat degradation resulting from coastal development, and probably climate change. As most of South Africa’s 191 shark species have ranges that extend well beyond South African waters, some of the decline in the RLI for South Africa’s sharks reflects fishing pressure and other threats beyond South Africa’s jurisdiction. When national adjustments in threat status are taken into account, the South African RLI is marginally higher and the declining trend is marginally less steep than the global RLI for the same set of species. Nevertheless, 6 of South Africa’s 13 endemic sharks are threatened with global extinction, with their future fully dependent on conservation and fisheries management actions in South Africa.


